I analyzed the 50000-row DepMap-style CRISPR dependency dataset using the local `dataset.parquet` file and the column descriptions in this bundle. More negative dependency scores were treated as stronger dependency after knockout. I screened single-feature effects for every dependency outcome, then ran dependency-specific subgroup and interaction searches over the strongest modifiers so the analysis did not stop at main effects.

For `dependency_BRAF`, the dominant signal was `feature_009 == 1`: mean BRAF dependency was -0.8047 in that subgroup versus -0.2495 otherwise, effect -0.5552, p effectively 0. The strongest descriptive subgroup combined `feature_009 == 1` with high `feature_016 >= 0.964` and had mean -0.8286 versus -0.2965 in all other lines. Interaction screening did not find a stronger independent modifier than the primary `feature_009` signal.

For `dependency_EGFR`, `feature_022 == 1` was the main dependency marker: mean -0.6010 versus -0.2524, effect -0.3486, p effectively 0. A refined subgroup with `feature_022 == 1`, `feature_011 == brain`, and `feature_016 >= 1.088` had mean -0.6770 versus -0.2788, effect -0.3983, p=6.7e-29, but the signal was still primarily anchored by `feature_022 == 1`.

For `dependency_ERBB2`, `feature_024 == 1` was strongly associated with more negative scores: mean -0.6856 versus -0.2535, effect -0.4321, p effectively 0. The `feature_024 == 1` and `feature_010 == her2_enriched` subgroup was still more negative, mean -0.7525 versus -0.2944, effect -0.4581, p=5.4e-53. Its interaction coefficient was -0.0671, p=0.037, supporting a modest additional HER2-enriched dependency component.

For `dependency_KRAS`, `feature_014 == 1` was the main signal: mean -0.5594 versus -0.2520, effect -0.3075, p effectively 0. The `feature_014 == 1` and `feature_016 >= 1.088` subgroup had mean -0.6092 versus -0.3177, effect -0.2915, p=1.3e-181. A separate interaction between `feature_016 >= 1.088` and `feature_020 == 1` was significant but smaller, coefficient -0.0596, p=0.00029.

For `dependency_RIT1`, `feature_027 == 1` was associated with stronger dependency: mean -0.3527 versus -0.2572, effect -0.0955, p=2.0e-70. The subgroup `feature_027 == 1` and `feature_007 <= -1.097` had mean -0.3857 versus -0.2648, effect -0.1209, p=3.6e-13. The corresponding interaction was not significant, so this appears to be a descriptive enrichment rather than an independent modifier.

The most striking heterogeneity was for `dependency_KIF18A`. `feature_011 == colorectal` alone had mean -0.7204 versus -0.2524, effect -0.4680, p effectively 0. The complete subgroup `feature_011 == colorectal`, `feature_035 == 1`, and `feature_028 >= 1.427` had mean -1.1961 versus -0.2678 in all other cell lines, effect -0.9282, p effectively 0. Two-way interaction tests supported the complete subgroup definition: colorectal x `feature_035 == 1` coefficient -0.6822, colorectal x high `feature_028` coefficient -0.6050, and high `feature_028` x `feature_035 == 1` coefficient -0.4952. This is the clearest multivariable dependency pattern in the dataset.

For `dependency_TMED10`, the main signal was smaller and tied to high `feature_016`: `feature_016 >= 1.088` had mean -0.2906 versus -0.2499, effect -0.0407, p=1.1e-14. The subgroup with both `feature_016 >= 1.088` and `feature_026 >= 1.153` had mean -0.3424 versus -0.2531, effect -0.0893, p=1.3e-08. The interaction coefficient was -0.0369, p=0.035, suggesting high `feature_026` amplifies the high-`feature_016` association.

For `dependency_DHX9`, `feature_016 >= 1.088` had mean -0.3727 versus -0.3293, effect -0.0433, p=4.3e-16. Heterogeneity search found an ovarian high-`feature_016` subgroup: `feature_016 >= 1.088` and `feature_011 == ovarian` had mean -0.4183 versus -0.3329, effect -0.0854, p=6.5e-07. The interaction coefficient was -0.0424, p=0.022.

For `dependency_POLR2A`, high `feature_016` was the major dependency marker: `feature_016 >= 1.088` had mean -0.5281 versus -0.4070, effect -0.1211, p=4.5e-119. The subgroup with `feature_016 >= 1.088` and `feature_026 >= 1.153` had mean -0.5552 versus -0.4177, effect -0.1375, p=1.1e-17. Pairwise interactions were weaker than the main feature_016 signal, so this is best interpreted as a high-`feature_016` dependency with descriptive high-`feature_026` enrichment.

For `dependency_RPL11`, `feature_003 >= 1.003` was the strongest single marker: mean -0.3831 versus -0.2573, effect -0.1257, p=2.4e-125. A three-feature subgroup, `feature_003 >= 1.003`, `feature_016 >= 0.964`, and `feature_023 >= 6.33`, had mean -0.4465 versus -0.2683, effect -0.1783, p=5.2e-27. A related `feature_003 >= 0.428` by `feature_023 >= 6.33` interaction had coefficient -0.0405, p=0.00016.

Overall, most canonical dependency outcomes had one dominant binary or thresholded marker (`feature_009` for BRAF, `feature_022` for EGFR, `feature_024` for ERBB2, `feature_014` for KRAS, `feature_027` for RIT1). In contrast, `dependency_KIF18A` showed the clearest multivariable subgroup: colorectal cell lines with `feature_035 == 1` and high `feature_028` were much more dependent than any single-feature contrast alone. Several housekeeping-like dependencies (`TMED10`, `DHX9`, `POLR2A`, `RPL11`) showed smaller but statistically robust associations with high `feature_016`, with outcome-specific modifiers adding subgroup enrichment.

 succeeded in 3923ms:
CRISPR Dependency Map analysis summary for ds001_depmap

I analyzed 50,000 cell-line records using only the local task bundle. More negative dependency scores were treated as stronger dependency. The workflow used Welch-style subgroup contrasts for binary/categorical predicates, Pearson/linear-regression scans for continuous features, and a systematic heterogeneity search over 120 candidate predicates per dependency outcome, including pair-subgroup screens and refined triple-subgroup checks. Thresholds such as 1.088 or 1.427 are empirical decile or quartile cut points from this dataset.

BRAF: The clearest BRAF dependency marker was feature_009 == 1. These lines had mean dependency_BRAF -0.8047 versus -0.2495 in feature_009 == 0 lines, effect -0.5552, p <= 1e-300. Pair searches retained feature_009 as the driver; feature_009 == 1 and feature_030 == 0 had nearly the same effect (-0.5514), so the best-supported BRAF rule is feature_009 == 1 rather than a more complex subgroup.

EGFR: feature_022 == 1 strongly marked EGFR dependency, with mean dependency_EGFR -0.6010 versus -0.2524 outside the subgroup, effect -0.3486, p <= 1e-300. A refined subgroup, feature_022 == 1 plus feature_023 >= 5.669 and feature_015 <= 3.230, was more concentrated (mean -0.6714; effect -0.3939), supporting heterogeneity around the feature_022 signal.

ERBB2: feature_024 == 1 was the dominant ERBB2 marker, mean -0.6856 versus -0.2535, effect -0.4321, p <= 1e-300. The strongest refined subgroup was feature_024 == 1, feature_011 == breast, and feature_013 >= 0.519, mean -0.7597 versus -0.2930, effect -0.4667. This supports an ERBB2 dependency concentrated within a breast/high-feature_013 subset of feature_024-positive lines.

KRAS: feature_014 == 1 was the strongest KRAS marker, mean -0.5594 versus -0.2520, effect -0.3075, p <= 1e-300. Pancreatic lineage (feature_011 == pancreatic) was also associated with more negative KRAS dependency (effect -0.1127). The refined subgroup feature_014 == 1, feature_016 >= 1.088, and feature_028 <= -0.406 had mean -0.6640, effect -0.3410, indicating stronger dependency in a high-feature_016/low-feature_028 subset.

RIT1: feature_027 == 1 was the main RIT1 marker, mean -0.3527 versus -0.2572, effect -0.0955, p <= 1e-300. Heterogeneity search found a more concentrated subgroup: feature_027 == 1, feature_011 == brain, and feature_008 == 0 had mean -0.4315 versus -0.2651, effect -0.1665, p = 3.33e-15.

KIF18A: This was the strongest multivariable dependency pattern. Colorectal lines (feature_011 == colorectal) had much more negative dependency_KIF18A than other lines (effect -0.4680), and high feature_028 (>= 1.427) was also strongly associated (effect -0.3773). The complete rule was feature_011 == colorectal, feature_028 >= 1.427, feature_020 == 0, and feature_035 == 1. This subgroup had mean dependency_KIF18A -1.3952 versus -0.2678 outside the subgroup, effect -1.1274, p <= 1e-300. Suppressor checks supported the full rule: within colorectal high-feature_028 lines, feature_020 == 1 had near-background mean -0.2642, and feature_035 == 0 had near-background mean -0.2849.

TMED10: TMED10 showed a weaker but significant broad pattern around feature_016. Lines with feature_016 >= 1.088 had mean -0.2906 versus -0.2499, effect -0.0407, p = 1.11e-14. The strongest refined subgroup was feature_016 >= 1.088, feature_026 >= 1.153, and feature_004 == adherent, mean -0.3578 versus -0.2532, effect -0.1046, p = 1.03e-9.

DHX9: High feature_016 and high feature_023 both marked DHX9 dependency. feature_016 >= 1.088 had effect -0.0433, and feature_023 >= 6.330 had effect -0.0314. The refined subgroup feature_016 >= 1.088, feature_023 >= 5.669, and feature_020 == 1 had mean -0.4472 versus -0.3332, effect -0.1139, p = 6.98e-6.

POLR2A: The POLR2A signal was dominated by feature_016. Lines with feature_016 >= 1.088 had mean -0.5281 versus -0.4070, effect -0.1211, p <= 1e-300. A refined subgroup, feature_016 >= 1.088, feature_018 == 1, and feature_005 == batch_c, had mean -0.5982 versus -0.4181, effect -0.1801, suggesting additional heterogeneity within high-feature_016 lines.

RPL11: High feature_003 was the strongest RPL11 marker, mean -0.3831 versus -0.2573, effect -0.1257, p <= 1e-300. feature_018 == 1 also supported RPL11 dependency, effect -0.1091. The most concentrated refined subgroup combined feature_003 >= 1.003, feature_016 >= 0.964, and feature_033 >= 0.602, mean -0.4600 versus -0.2684, effect -0.1916, p <= 1e-300.

Overall conclusion: Several dependencies were driven by single strong binary markers: feature_009 for BRAF, feature_022 for EGFR, feature_024 for ERBB2, feature_014 for KRAS, and feature_027 for RIT1. Other outcomes showed broader continuous-feature gradients, especially feature_016 for TMED10, DHX9, and POLR2A, and feature_003 for RPL11. The most biologically notable heterogeneity pattern was KIF18A, where the dependency was not simply colorectal or high feature_028 alone but required the complete subgroup feature_011 == colorectal, feature_028 >= 1.427, feature_020 == 0, and feature_035 == 1; either feature_020 == 1 or feature_035 == 0 suppressed the dependency back toward background.

 succeeded in 5881ms:
Dataset ds001_depmap contains 50000 cell-line records, 36 anonymized cell-line features, and 10 CRISPR dependency outcomes. More negative dependency scores indicate stronger dependency. I analyzed the local Parquet file only, using difference-in-means tests and a systematic subgroup search over categorical levels, binary features, and top/bottom quartiles of continuous features. For each dependency outcome, I also checked two-predicate subgroup definitions to look for heterogeneity beyond main effects.

The clearest driver-like main effects were large and highly significant. `feature_009 == 1` marked strong `dependency_BRAF` sensitivity: mean -0.804698 versus -0.249503 outside the group, effect -0.555195, p approximately 1e-300. `feature_022 == 1` similarly marked `dependency_EGFR` sensitivity: mean -0.601046 versus -0.252407, effect -0.348638, p approximately 1e-300. `feature_024 == 1` marked `dependency_ERBB2` sensitivity: mean -0.685595 versus -0.253473, effect -0.432122, p approximately 1e-300. `feature_014 == 1` marked `dependency_KRAS` sensitivity: mean -0.559415 versus -0.251959, effect -0.307456, p approximately 1e-300.

Lineage refinement did not improve those four driver-like dependencies as much as the main binary features. For example, `feature_009 == 1` plus skin lineage had strong `dependency_BRAF` sensitivity (effect -0.520456), but the broader `feature_009 == 1` split remained cleaner. The same pattern held for `dependency_EGFR` with brain lineage, `dependency_ERBB2` with breast or gastric lineage, and `dependency_KRAS` with pancreatic or colorectal lineage: all subgroup tests were significant, but the binary features were the main dependency-defining predicates.

`dependency_RIT1` had a weaker but clear main effect for `feature_027 == 1`: mean -0.352716 versus -0.257196, effect -0.095520, p approximately 1e-300. The heterogeneity search found stronger refined subgroups. The small `feature_027 == 1` and brain subgroup had mean -0.404687 versus -0.264988 outside, effect -0.139699, p=1.217e-13. A larger refined subgroup, `feature_027 == 1` and `feature_023 <= 4.230`, had mean -0.376141 versus -0.263323, effect -0.112818, p approximately 1e-300.

The strongest non-driver heterogeneous signal was for `dependency_KIF18A`. Colorectal lineage alone (`feature_011 == "colorectal"`) was strongly negative (mean -0.720354 versus -0.252397, effect -0.467957, p approximately 1e-300), and high `feature_028` alone was also negative (mean -0.469402 versus -0.252593, effect -0.216810, p approximately 1e-300). The two-by-two table showed the effect required both conditions: non-colorectal/low-`feature_028` mean -0.252267, non-colorectal/high-`feature_028` mean -0.252941, colorectal/low-`feature_028` mean -0.259003, and colorectal/high-`feature_028` mean -0.928802. The interaction contrast was -0.669125. Adding `feature_035 == 1` identified the strongest complete subgroup: `feature_011 == "colorectal"`, `feature_028 >= 0.819`, and `feature_035 == 1` had mean -1.111866 versus -0.253014 outside, effect -0.858852, p approximately 1e-300. Within colorectal/high-`feature_028` lines, `feature_035 == 1` had mean -1.111866 while `feature_035 == 0` had mean -0.271825, so `feature_035` appears to enable the dependency.

The broader essential-like outcomes showed smaller but reproducible dependencies. `dependency_TMED10` was modestly more negative in high-`feature_016` lines (`feature_016 >= 0.964`): mean -0.281605 versus -0.244729, effect -0.036876, p approximately 1e-300. The refined high-`feature_016` plus luminal subgroup (`feature_010 == "luminal"`) had effect -0.043545, p=8.138e-5. `dependency_DHX9` was also more negative in high-`feature_016` lines (effect -0.037084, p approximately 1e-300), with the strongest refined subgroup at high `feature_016` and high `feature_023` (`feature_023 >= 5.669`): effect -0.059477, p approximately 1e-300.

`dependency_POLR2A` had the strongest broad high-`feature_016` effect among this group: mean -0.497174 versus -0.392828, effect -0.104346, p approximately 1e-300. Pairwise subgroup refinements remained significant but did not improve meaningfully on the high-`feature_016` main effect. `dependency_RPL11` was instead most tied to high `feature_003` (`feature_003 >= 0.428`): mean -0.343967 versus -0.245214, effect -0.098753, p approximately 1e-300. The best refined subgroup combined high `feature_003` and high `feature_016`, with mean -0.376555 versus -0.261555, effect -0.114999, p approximately 1e-300.

Overall conclusions: the strongest dependency-specific patterns were `feature_009` for BRAF, `feature_022` for EGFR, `feature_024` for ERBB2, `feature_014` for KRAS, and a multivariable colorectal/high-`feature_028`/`feature_035 == 1` subgroup for KIF18A. RIT1 showed a weaker `feature_027` signal with low-`feature_023` heterogeneity. TMED10, DHX9, POLR2A, and RPL11 showed smaller but statistically robust associations with high `feature_016` or high `feature_003`, with selected two-feature refinements.

